    "#Q1: What are the Probability Mass Function (PMF) and Probability Density Function (PDF)? Explain with an example.\n",
    "\n",
    "#A1 A probability mass function (PMF) gives the probability that a discrete random variable is exactly equal to some value while\n",
    "#A probability density function (PDF) describes the relative likelihood for a continuous random variable to take on a given value\n",
    "\n",
    "#Example PDF and PMF\n",
    "#For example, suppose we roll a dice one time. If we let X denote the number that the dice lands on, then the PMF of X is:\n",
    "#P(X = x) = {1/6 if x = 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 or 6 ; 0 otherwise} each possible outcome has an equal probability of 1/6 and any other value has zero probability.\n",
    "\n",
    "#For example, suppose we measure the length of a randomly chosen wood stick in centimeters. If we let X denote this length, then the PDF of X is:\n",
    "\n",
    "#f(x) = {1/5 if 0 < x < 15; 0 otherwise}\n",
    "\n",
    "#This means that any length between 0 and 5 cm has an equal probability density of 1/5 and any other length has zero probability density."
   ]
